#Text=Terence MacManus
#Text=Trial of the Irish patriots at Clonmel .
#Text=Thomas Francis Meagher , MacManus , and Patrick O'Donoghue receiving their sentences of death .
#Text=Grave of Terence Bellew MacManus in the Fenian Plot , Glasnevin , Dublin .
#Text=Terence Bellew MacManus ( born 1811 or 1823 – 15 January 1861 ) was an Irish rebel who participated in the Young Irelander Rebellion of 1848 .
#Text=Sentenced to death for treason , he and several other participants were given commuted sentences in 1849 and transported for life to Van Diemen 's Land in Australia .
#Text=Three years later in 1852 , MacManus escaped and emigrated to the United States .
#Text=He lived in San Francisco , California until his death in 1861 .
#Text=There he was unable to re-establish his career .
#Text=His body was returned to Dublin for burial , where the Fenians gave him a large funeral in honor of his part in the rebellion .
#Text=MacManus was notable for his statement in court in 1848 ; he explained his actions by saying : " ... [ I]t was not because I loved England less , but because I loved Ireland more . "
#Text=Biography
#Text=Terence MacManus was born about 1811 ( or 1823 ) [ 1 ] in Tempo , County Fermanagh , Ireland .
#Text=He was educated in parochial schools .
#Text=As a young man he moved to Liverpool , a major port , where he became a successful shipping agent .
#Text=In 1848 he returned to Ireland , where he became active in the Repeal Association , which sought to overturn the Act of Union between Great Britain and Ireland .

#Text=After joining the Irish Confederation , he was among those who took part with William Smith O'Brien and John Blake Dillon in the July 1848 Young Irelander Rebellion in Ballingarry , County Tipperary .
#Text=MacManus and the other leaders were charged and convicted of treason , and sentenced to death for their actions . [ 1 ]
#Text=Due to public support for clemency , the men 's sentences were commuted to deportation for life .
#Text=MacManus was transported to Van Diemen 's Land in Tasmania , Australia in 1849 on the Swift , together with O'Brien , Thomas Francis Meagher and Patrick O'Donoghue .
#Text=They were assigned to different settlements to reduce their collaboration in the new land .
#Text=However , the Irish men continued to meet secretly . [ 2 ]
#Text=In 1852 MacManus and Meagher escaped from Australia and made their way to San Francisco , California , where MacManus settled .
#Text=( Meagher went on to New York City . )
#Text=Like other immigrants , the Irish revolutionaries carried their issues to the United States .
#Text=Ellis , captain of a ship that was supposed to carry O'Brien to freedom , also emigrated to San Francisco .
#Text=MacManus held a lynch court of Ellis among Irish emigrants for his betrayal of O'Brien in his escape attempt from Van Diemen 's Land .
#Text=The court martial acquitted Ellis for lack of evidence .
#Text=Failing to re-establish his career as a shipping agent , MacManus died in poverty around the age of 50 .
#Text=His body was returned to Ireland , here he was buried in Glasnevin Cemetery , Dublin , on 10 November 1861 .
#Text=Fenians organized a huge funeral and nationalist demonstration to honor MacManus .
#Text=Quotes
#Text=From the dock before sentencing , 24 October 1848 : [ 3 ]
#Text=...

#Text=" I say , whatever part I may have taken in the struggle for my country 's independence , whatever part I may have acted in my short career , I stand before you , my lords , with a free heart and a light conscience , to abide the issue of your sentence .

#Text=And now , my lords , this is , perhaps , the fittest time to put a sentence upon record , which is this - that standing in this dock , and called to ascend the scaffold - it may be to-morrow - it may be now - it may be never - whatever the result may be , I wish to put this on record , that in the part I have taken I was not actuated by enmity towards Englishmen - for among them I have passed some of the happiest days of my life , and the most prosperous ; and in no part which I have taken was I actuated by enmity towards Englishmen individually , whatever I may have felt of the injustice of English rule in this island ; I therefore say , that it is not because I loved England less , but because I loved Ireland more , that I now stand before you  .
